    "body": "Closes #12716\r\n## Summary\r\n- Add fused CUDA kernel combining cross-head (full-dim) RMSNorm + RoPE into a single pass over the packed QKV tensor\r\n- Eliminates extra global memory round-trip between separate norm and RoPE ops\r\n- Supports interleaved and rotate_half RoPE modes, with CTA-level shared-memory reduction\r\n- Enable by default for WAN (replaces the previous unfused path)\r\n## Changes\r\n- `fusedDiTQKNormRopeKernel.cu/h` — cross-head kernel + launcher\r\n- `fusedDiTQKNormRopeOp.cpp` — torch op binding\r\n- `utils.py` — inplace op registration for torch.compile\r\n- `attention.py` — dispatch to cross-head kernel when `qk_norm_mode == \"full\"`\r\n- `transformer_wan.py` — enable fused kernel by default for WAN\r\n- `test_fused_dit_qk_norm_rope.py` — correctness tests (interleaved, rotate_half, batched, V-unchanged)\r\n## Test plan\r\n- `pytest tests/unittest/_torch/thop/parallel/test_fused_dit_qk_norm_rope.py`\r\n- Cross-head correctness validated against PyTorch reference for WAN 1.3B (12 heads) and 14B (40 heads)\r\n- Both interleaved and rotate_half RoPE modes tested\r\n- V-unchanged tests confirm only Q/K are modified\r\n- Batched input (B > 1) with tiled cos/sin embeddings\r\n\r\n## Performance\r\n\r\nMeasured on a single A100 80GB PCIe, BF16 inputs, with the new benchmark\r\n`tests/unittest/_torch/thop/parallel/bench_fused_dit_cross_head_qk_norm_rope.py`.\r\n\r\nThree implementations are compared:\r\n\r\n1. **Eager** — PyTorch eager-mode split RMSNorm + RoPE (the path WAN previously used).\r\n2. **Compile** — `torch.compile(..., mode=\"reduce-overhead\")` of (1); TorchInductor fuses the elementwise + norm into Triton kernels.\r\n3. **Fused** — the single CUDA kernel added in this PR.\r\n\r\nTimed via CUDA events, GPU-side only.\r\n\r\n### RoPE: interleave (WAN-1)\r\n\r\n| Config              | Eager (ms) | Compile (ms) | Fused (ms) | vs Eager  | vs Compile |\r\n| ------------------- | ---------: | -----------: | ---------: | --------: | ---------: |\r\n| WAN-1.3B  256 tok   |     0.3756 |       0.1110 | **0.0088** | **42.6×** |  **12.6×** |\r\n| WAN-1.3B  4096 tok  |     1.0012 |       0.1630 | **0.0978** | **10.2×** |  **1.67×** |\r\n| WAN-14B   256 tok   |     0.4213 |       0.1089 | **0.0131** | **32.1×** |   **8.3×** |\r\n| WAN-14B   4096 tok  |     3.2604 |       0.4628 | **0.2086** | **15.6×** |  **2.22×** |\r\n| WAN-14B   16384 tok |    12.4497 |       1.8080 | **0.8108** | **15.4×** |  **2.23×** |\r\n\r\n### RoPE: rotate_half (WAN-2)\r\n\r\n| Config              | Eager (ms) | Compile (ms) | Fused (ms) | vs Eager  | vs Compile |\r\n| ------------------- | ---------: | -----------: | ---------: | --------: | ---------: |\r\n| WAN-1.3B  256 tok   |     0.4739 |       0.1004 | **0.0092** | **51.3×** |  **10.9×** |\r\n| WAN-1.3B  4096 tok  |     0.8287 |       0.1381 | **0.1117** |  **7.4×** |  **1.24×** |\r\n| WAN-14B   256 tok   |     0.5396 |       0.1057 | **0.0158** | **34.1×** |   **6.7×** |\r\n| WAN-14B   4096 tok  |     2.7099 |       0.4374 | **0.2298** | **11.8×** |  **1.90×** |\r\n| WAN-14B   16384 tok |    10.2461 |       1.7035 | **0.9017** | **11.4×** |  **1.89×** |\r\n\r\n### Estimated end-to-end impact on WAN-14B (40 transformer blocks)\r\n\r\nThe kernel runs once per self-attention layer, so per forward pass:\r\n\r\n| Shape            | Per-fwd vs Eager (saved) | Per-fwd vs Compile (saved) |\r\n| ---------------- | -----------------------: | -------------------------: |\r\n| 14B @ 4k tokens  |                  ~122 ms |                     ~10 ms |\r\n| 14B @ 16k tokens |                ~466 ms |                     ~40 ms |\r\n\r\nAgainst a typical WAN-14B forward pass (~0.5–0.8 s at 4k tokens, ~2–4 s at 16k tokens), this maps to roughly **~15% end-to-end speedup vs eager** and **~1.5–2% vs `torch.compile`**. (These are estimates derived from the kernel-level measurements above; a full end-to-end measurement was not run.)\r\n\r\n## Measured DRAM Bandwidth (ncu)\r\n\r\nMeasured on a single **NVIDIA A100 80GB PCIe** . Both columns below are direct ncu metrics:\r\n\r\n- **DRAM BW (GB/s)** — ncu metric `dram__bytes.sum.per_second`\r\n- **DRAM % of peak** — ncu metric `dram__throughput.avg.pct_of_peak_sustained_elapsed`\r\n\r\n### WAN-14B (40 heads × 128 head_dim)\r\n\r\n| Tokens | RoPE mode    | DRAM BW (GB/s) | DRAM % of peak |\r\n| -----: | :----------- | -------------: | -------------: |\r\n|    256 | interleave   |        **267** |          13.8% |\r\n|    256 | rotate_half  |        **225** |          11.6% |\r\n|   4096 | interleave   |        **621** |          32.1% |\r\n|   4096 | rotate_half  |        **550** |          28.4% |\r\n|  16384 | interleave   |        **681** |          35.2% |\r\n|  16384 | rotate_half  |        **607** |          31.6% |\r\n\r\n### WAN-1.3B (12 heads × 128 head_dim)\r\n\r\n| Tokens | RoPE mode    | DRAM BW (GB/s) | DRAM % of peak |\r\n| -----: | :----------- | -------------: | -------------: |\r\n|    256 | interleave   |        **144** |           7.5% |\r\n|    256 | rotate_half  |        **134** |           7.0% |\r\n|   4096 | interleave   |        **280** |          14.5% |\r\n|   4096 | rotate_half  |        **246** |          12.7% |\r\n\r\n### Notes\r\n\r\n- WAN-14B at sequence lengths (4k, 16k) sits at **~32–35% of HBM peak** for `interleave` and **~28–32%** for `rotate_half`. SM throughput is **53–62%** of peak in parallel, so neither pipe is saturated; ncu flags the kernel as partially latency-bound.\r\n\r\n### Performance (B200)\r\n\r\nSame benchmark, BF16 inputs, on a single **NVIDIA B200**.\r\n\r\n#### RoPE: interleave (WAN-1)\r\n\r\n| Config            | Eager (ms) | Compile (ms) | Fused (ms) | vs Eager  | vs Compile |\r\n| ----------------- | ---------- | ------------ | ---------- | --------- | ---------- |\r\n| WAN-1.3B 256 tok  | 0.1824     | 0.0691       | **0.0082** | **22.2×** | **8.4×**   |\r\n| WAN-1.3B 4096 tok | 0.3617     | 0.0821       | **0.0737** | **4.91×** | **1.11×**  |\r\n| WAN-14B 256 tok   | 0.1848     | 0.0547       | **0.0103** | **18.0×** | **5.33×**  |\r\n| WAN-14B 4096 tok  | 1.1180     | 0.2061       | **0.1254** | **8.91×** | **1.64×**  |\r\n| WAN-14B 16384 tok | 4.1947     | 0.8102       | **0.5410** | **7.75×** | **1.50×**  |\r\n\r\nAll three paths (Eager, Compile, Fused) are faster on B200 than on A100 in absolute wall-clock time, as expected from B200's higher SM count, larger per-SM shared memory, and ~5× HBM bandwidth. The fused kernel still beats eager by 5–22× and `torch.compile` by 1.1–8.4× across all configs. The relative margin vs `torch.compile` is smaller than on A100 because TorchInductor regenerates significantly better Triton schedules for sm_100, so the baseline it competes against is stronger on B200.\r\n\r\n<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->\r\n## Summary by CodeRabbit\r\n\r\n* **New Features**\r\n  * Added fused cross-head QK normalization and RoPE operation for optimized tensor processing.\r\n  * Support for interleaved and rotate_half RoPE execution modes.\r\n  * Updated attention modules to dispatch to appropriate fused kernels based on normalization configuration.\r\n\r\n* **Tests**\r\n  * Comprehensive test coverage for cross-head normalization with both RoPE variants and batched scenarios.\r\n<!-- end of auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nPlease write the PR title by following this template:\r\n\r\n**[JIRA ticket/NVBugs ID/GitHub issue/None][type] Summary**\r\n\r\nValid ticket formats:\r\n  - JIRA ticket: [TRTLLM-1234] or [FOOBAR-123] for other FOOBAR project\r\n  - NVBugs ID: [https://nvbugs/1234567]\r\n  - GitHub issue: [#1234]\r\n  - No ticket: [None]\r\n\r\nValid types (lowercase): [fix], [feat], [doc], [infra], [chore], etc.\r\n\r\nExamples:\r\n  - [TRTLLM-1234][feat] Add new feature\r\n  - [https://nvbugs/1234567][fix] Fix some bugs\r\n  - [#1234][doc] Update documentation\r\n  - [None][chore] Minor clean-up\r\n\r\nAlternative (faster) way using CodeRabbit AI:\r\n\r\n**[JIRA ticket/NVBugs ID/GitHub issue/None] @coderabbitai title**\r\n\r\nNOTE: \"@coderabbitai title\" will be replaced by the title generated by CodeRabbit AI, that includes the \"[type]\" and title.\r\nFor more info, see /.coderabbit.yaml.\r\n\r\n-->\r\n\r\n## Description\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nPlease explain the issue and the solution in short.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n## Test Coverage\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nPlease list clearly what are the relevant test(s) that can safeguard the changes in the PR. This helps us to ensure we have sufficient test coverage for the PR.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n## PR Checklist\r\n\r\nPlease review the following before submitting your PR:\r\n- PR description clearly explains what and why. If using CodeRabbit's summary, please make sure it makes sense.\r\n- PR Follows [TRT-LLM CODING GUIDELINES](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/blob/main/CODING_GUIDELINES.md) to the best of your knowledge.\r\n- Test cases are provided for new code paths (see [test instructions](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/tree/main/tests#1-how-does-the-ci-work))\r\n- Any new dependencies have been scanned for license and vulnerabilities\r\n- [CODEOWNERS](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/blob/main/.github/CODEOWNERS) updated if ownership changes\r\n- Documentation updated as needed\r\n- Update [tava architecture diagram](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/blob/main/.github/tava_architecture_diagram.md) if there is a significant design change in PR.\r\n- The reviewers assigned automatically/manually are appropriate for the PR.\r\n\r\n\r\n- [x] Please check this after reviewing the above items as appropriate for this PR.\r\n\r\n## GitHub Bot Help\r\n\r\nTo see a list of available CI bot commands, please comment `/bot help`.\r\n",
